AVIAN INFLUENZA (39): UK (ENGLAND) NOT H5 or H7
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 18 Apr 2013
Source: Mail Online [summ., edited]
http://tinyurl.com/bwp4lf3


Thousands of turkeys are being treated for the symptoms of bird flu at a factory farm operated by the Bernard Matthews group.

Tests are being carried out after signs of the disease were spotted at the farm in Suffolk, which is where the food giant is based.

The Government's food and farming department Defra yesterday confirmed that its experts have detected a strain of the virus at the farm.

Any evidence of bird flu is taken extremely seriously and historically has led to major culls in order to prevent any spread of the virus. On this occasion the company claims that the 5000 turkeys involved, which are used as breeding stock, can be successfully treated with antibiotics, rather than being destroyed.

A Defra spokesman said: "We are awaiting further laboratory test results from an on-going investigation into suspect avian disease at a premises in the South East.
"The premises remains under restriction pending further results.
"Public Health England are aware and are ready to take the necessary action pending further test results.'

Bernard Matthews died in November 2010 but his company still runs 56 farms across Norfolk, Suffolk and Lincolnshire.
A company spokesman said: "On Sunday the birds were displaying symptoms of ill health, which Bernard Matthews recognised as bird flu because of previous outbreaks.
"We notified Defra, which agreed and has since ruled out the illness as being the H5 and H7 forms of the virus -- the notifiable strains which can be transferred from birds to humans.
"Prior to Defra's arrival we treated the birds with antibiotics and the birds have been getting better since."

He added: "I would like to stress -- there is no risk whatsoever to humans from this outbreak."

The Bernard Matthews company was heavily criticised in 2007 following the discovery of a strain of the H5N1 type of bird flu on a major farm and processing centre in Holton, Suffolk. An official inquiry found that the firm had failed to put right a series of health and hygiene failures that allowed the virus to spread. Squalid conditions at the farm and processing factory in Suffolk were implicated in triggering the outbreak of the virus which led to the slaughter of 159 000 young turkeys. Subsequently, hundreds of farms in East Anglia were effectively placed into quarantine and banned from moving their poultry.

[Byline: Sean Poulter]

