[The source of infection in the described turkeys is, most probably, wild birds. In 2007, a free-range turkey flock belonging to the same firm was found infected by HPAI H5N1, followed by eradication of the outbreak (see ProMED-mail posting 20071114.3693). In 2009, LPAI H6N1 was reported (see ProMED-mail posting 20090301.0852).

Avian influenza (AI) is caused by specified viruses that are members of the family _Orthomyxoviridae_ and placed in the genus _Influenzavirus A_. There are 3 influenza genera -- A, B, and C; only influenza A viruses are known to infect birds.

There are 16 haemagglutinin (H1-16) and 9 neuraminidase (N1-9) subtypes of influenza A virus. Any highly pathogenic avian influenza isolate (HPAI) is classified as notifiable avian influenza (NAI) virus. Although all naturally occurring virulent strains isolated to date have been either of the H5 or H7 subtype, most H5 or H7 isolates have been of low pathogenicity (LPAI). Due to the risk of a LPAI H5 or H7 subtype becoming virulent by mutation in poultry hosts, all H5 and H7 viruses -- including low-pathogenic ones -- have also been classified as NAI viruses.

According to Defra, initial tests have ruled out the H5 or H7 strains of the disease (https://www.gov.uk/government/news/avian-influenza-testing). Results of the tests to define the subtype and the pathogenicity are expected. The prescribed laboratory methods for the identification of the virus and for the determination of its pathogenicity rate are described in OIE's terrestrial manual; see at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.03.04_AI.pdf.

If the causative agent is found to be of low pathogenicity, the event is not regarded as notifiable. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/6nGB.]
